The hydro/solvothermal approach is the most widely used for the synthesis of CDs effective in the fate of plastic waste (
                        Table 1
                        ) maybe because the nanoparticles produced by thermal decomposition lack size uniformity [28]. Microwave heating can quickly produce homogeneous heating with fast volumetric heating without a thermal conduction process, in contrast to conventional external heating methods. However, the reaction temperature in an open system cannot rise above the boiling point of the solvent. An option is to combine the hydro/solvothermal and microwave techniques. The microwave-hydro/solvothermal approach merges the advantages of the two processes, resulting in high temperature and pressure with less preparation time. However, it is less used for the synthesis of CDs effective in the fate of plastic waste (
                        Table 1
                        ) 
                        [66]. The synthesis conditions are just as important as the effectiveness of the type of synthesis method in the production of CDs. For instance, the C-C backbones on plastic structures are hard to break, so robust oxidative chemicals like H2SO4, HNO3, H2O2, and KMnO4 are typically needed to prompt dehydrogenation of the conversion process [67–69]. Although these current methods can handle real-world plastic waste, they frequently use toxic or corrosive chemicals and high temperatures, which raises energy costs and environmental concerns and presents significant difficulties for large-scale applications. Therefore, it is still desirable to develop a low-cost, highly efficient, and environmentally friendly synthetic technology that has a high yield and is simple to scale up. Several researchers have sought to offer solutions in this regard using hydrothermal and thermal calcination processes [63,70–72] but more research is needed in this field to solve all the existing challenges.

Plastic waste have been widely utilized to produce CDs as low-cost and plentiful carbon sources. These materials are basically composed of carbon and hydrogen elements (

                           Fig. 4
                           ), which are also the main elements that make CDs. Additionally, heteroatom doping such as nitrogen and oxygen helps control the characteristics of CDs for various applications. We can divide the common polymer waste used as a precursor for the synthesis of CDs into two categories based on the type of elements they contain: first, polymers with carbon and hydrogen atoms, which mostly include PE, PP, and PS; second, polymers with heteroatoms (atoms other than carbon and hydrogen), which primarily include PET, PU, and PLA. Therefore, the waste of these plastics is a suitable precursor for the synthesis of CDs.

Yin et al. made CD-FMs using an easy, mild, and in-situ method for the detection of PE in the presence of agglomerated silica (SiO2) nanoparticles. First, SiO2 nanoparticles were dissolved in toluene and then added to PE solution in toluene, and the heat was applied to obtain a fluorescence mixture. After drying, the PE films had a strong blue fluorescence, which is related to the presence of CDs. They showed that CD-labeled PE samples could be easily detected visually by 367 nm light irradiation (

                           Fig. 9
                           ). Therefore, the marked PE can be used as a label material in the masterbatches to identify the components and in recycling [14].

Recently, Zhang et al. synthesized boron doped CDs using pyrene nitrate and boric acid through the solvothermal method, which has been used to identify and track MPs. These CDs showed a hydrophobic affinity to plastic and gave the plastic a fluorescence emission property. CDs can distinguish different MPs under 365 nm excitation according to color and fluorescence intensity. Polyvinyl chloride (PVC), PP, PE, and PS show bright magenta, bright yellow, light yellow, and light pink, respectively. Inconsistent color emission was detected in various types of MPs owing to the impact of the plastic medium on the CD environment (

                           Fig. 11
                           ). CDs alone do not emit fluorescence, so they can be used as a probe for tracking MPs in the “on” state, which is caused by the blend of MPs and CDs. The capability of CDs to detect MPs in soil and water models has been proven and semi-quantification has been done using ImageJ software. This system can be performed using UV light without any complicated apparatuses and provides a step towards rapid tracking of MPs under natural conditions [13].

For example, the most common cellulose derivative used in commercial thermoplastic applications is cellulose acetate (CA) [147]. Unfortunately, unlike cellulose, this polymer can remain in the environment for years depending on the location and environmental conditions [148]. If disposed of improperly, it releases a series of strands into the environment that can be considered MPs [149]. A group produced CDs by hydrothermal method with the help of microwave and cellulose oxidation. CA films modified with CD (CA+CD) were exposed to UV-A radiation. CDs as photocatalysts have the ability to stimulate CA degradation under simulated sunlight (

                           Fig. 14
                           ). The presence of CDs leads to the production of free radicals under UV radiation from O2, H2O, and H2O2. This process causes deacetylation and the formation of small molecules and regeneration of cellulose fibers. Since cellulose is biodegradable, this deacetylation is expected to make the material completely biodegradable [16].
